Synchronous programming refers to a sequence of operations that are executed one after another without any interruption or parallel execution. In this type of programming, a function will not return until all the code within it has been fully executed. This means that if there's an operation like reading data from a file or making an API call, the rest of the program will wait for it to complete before moving forward.

Asynchronous programming, on the other hand, allows operations to be executed independently and tasks can run concurrently without blocking the entire program execution. When an asynchronous function is called, it does not stop the execution of subsequent lines of code. Once the asynchronous operation completes, a callback function is executed with the result.

Example of Synchronous Programming:

```javascript
function syncFunction() {
  console.log("Step 1");
  // The following readFileSync method is a synchronous operation
  const data = fs.readFileSync("example.txt", "utf-8");
  console.log("Data:", data);
  console.log("Step 3");
}

syncFunction();
```

Example of Asynchronous Programming:

```javascript
function asyncFunction(callback) {
  console.log("Step 1");
  // The following readFile method is an asynchronous operation
  fs.readFile("example.txt", "utf-8", (err, data) => {
    if (!err) {
      console.log("Data:", data);
    }
    callback();
  });
}

asyncFunction(() => {
  console.log("Step 3");
});
```

In the synchronous example, "Step 1", "Data: (content of example.txt)", and "Step 3" will be printed in order because readFileSync is a blocking operation. In contrast, in the asynchronous example, "Step 1" and "Step 3" might not be executed sequentially due to the non-blocking nature of fs.readFile() function.
